etymologies: late Middle English. From quick + -ing. Compare Middle Low German quickinge reviving, refreshing
late Middle English. Either from quick + -ing or from quick + -ing

definitions: The action or process of planting a quickset hedge (usually hawthorn). Also : the plants used to make such a hedge collectively. Compare "quick", "quick".

etymologies: late 18th century; earliest use found in William Richardson (1743–1814), literary scholar. From quick + -ing

definitions: The action or process of coating metal with mercury or a solution containing mercury so as to facilitate the adherence of a layer of gold or silver to the metal surface.
